{"cursor":"39299","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{multiple issues|\n\n\n}}\n\n'Infomercials', also known as Direct Response TV (DRTV), are television\ncommercials which generally include a phone number or website. There are long-\nform infomercials, which are typically between 15 and 30 minutes in length, and\nshort-form infomercials, which are typically 30 seconds to 120 seconds in\nlength. [http://www.businessdictionary.com/definition/infomercial.html\nInfomercial] - Business Dictionary - CopyrightÂ©2010 WebFinance,\nInc. [http://www.yourdictionary.com/infomercial Infomercial\nDefinition] - Your Dictionary - Â© 1996-2010 LoveToKnow, Corp. [http://definitions.uslegal.com/a/advertising-media-\ninfomercials/ Advertising Media Infomercials Law & Legal Definition] - US Legal\nDefinitions - Copyright Â© 2001-2010 USLegal, Inc. Infomercials are also\nknown as 'paid programming' (or 'teleshopping' in Europe). This phenomenon\nstarted in the United States where infomercials were typically shown overnight\n(usually 2:00 a.m. to 6:00 a.m.), outside of prime time commercial broadcasting\npeak hours. Some television stations chose to air infomercials as an alternative\nto the former practice of signing off. By 2009, most US infomercial spending is\nduring early morning, daytime, and evening hours. Stations in most countries\naround the world have instituted similar media structures. According to\ntapebeat.com, over $150 billion of consumer products in the US are sold through\ninfomercials.\n\nWhile the term \"infomercial\" was originally applied only to television\nadvertising, it is now sometimes used to refer to any presentation (often on\nvideo) which presents a significant amount of information in an actual, or\nperceived, attempt to promote a point of view. When used this way, the term may\nbe meant to carry an implication that the party making the communication is\nexaggerating truths or hiding important facts. Often, it is unclear whether the\nactual presentation fits this definition because the term is used in an attempt\nto discredit the presentation. Hence, political speeches or conventions may be\nderogatorily referred to as \"infomercials\" for a specific point of view. [http://www.gmanews.tv/story/172527/premature-poll-campaign-law-cant-\nstop-infomercials \"Premature poll campaign law can't stop infomercials\"] - 2007\nÂ© GMA Network Inc.\n","linknr":577,"url":"Infomercial","recorded":1375086752,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Infomercial&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Infomercial&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Adult_Swim","/wiki/Paid_Programming_(TV_pilot)","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/f/f4/Ambox_content.png","//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Infomercial&action=edit","/wiki/Talk:Infomercial","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Infomercial&action=edit","/wiki/Help:Introduction_to_referencing/1","/wiki/Template:Citation_needed","/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability#Burden_of_evidence","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bd/Ambox_globe_content.svg/48px-Ambox_globe_content.svg.png","/wiki/Wikipedia:WikiPr